  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real issue that affects people like me who've worked in trades and seen firsthand how stereotypes can hold back talented individuals. Growing up in Chicago as an immigrant with parents who didn't have much education themselves, I know how important it is to feel confident in your abilities. Stereotype threat happens when someone internalizes the belief that they belong in a group that's been historically underrepresented in a field, like STEM, which makes them anxious and underperforms. For instance, a young woman working on electrical systems might feel she's not 'good enough' because she's a woman in a field where men dominate. This anxiety can lead to mistakes, like misreading circuit diagrams or skipping steps in a repair job. I've seen this happen in my own work with students and colleagues—when someone starts doubting themselves because of a stereotype, they stop trying as hard as they could. The question of whether we should address it is obvious: yes, absolutely. But the way we do it matters. We need to create environments where people feel safe to make mistakes without judgment. At my shop, we have a 'no-blame' policy when things go wrong, which helps reduce that anxiety. We also encourage people to share their experiences without fear of being labeled. It's not about fixing the person but fixing the environment so they can thrive. If we don't address stereotype threat, we're missing out on talent that could be valuable in our communities. My anxiety about this issue makes me want to do something tangible, like mentoring young people who might feel they don't belong in STEM fields. After all, everyone deserves to feel they can contribute their best.",
